{{Infobox official post | post = Downing Street Press Secretary | insignia = Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom (HM Government).svg | insigniacaption = Royal Arms as used by [[Her Majesty's Government]] | incumbent = Paul Harrison | incumbentsince = 26 July 2017 | department = [[10 Downing Street#Prime Minister's Office|Prime Minister's Office]] | appointer = [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] | formation = 1945 | first = [[Francis Williams, Baron Francis-Williams|Baron Francis-Williams]] | website = [http://www.number10.gov.uk/ 10 Downing Street] }}
The '''Downing Street Press Secretary''' is an advisor to the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] on news media and how to manage the image of the British government to the press. The position is part of the Prime Minister's Office and involves using information on what is happening in the UK and around the world, to decide on how the Prime Minister should present his or her reaction to the media. The incumbent also advises on how to handle news stories and other information which could affect the current Prime Minister or the Ministry.
The current Press Secretary is Paul Harrison, following the resignation of [[Lizzie Loudon]] on 18 April 2017.
==Role== The Press Secretary will address the lobby correspondents at 10 Downing Street to give journalists information on events attended by the Prime Minister, as well as current affairs in [[Downing Street]] and in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]].<ref name="A-Z Lobby">{{cite web|title=Lobby correspondents|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/a-z_of_parliament/h-l/82525.stm|website=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=29 September 2015|date=1 October 2008}}</ref> The Press Secretary works within the [[10 Downing Street#Prime Minister's Office|Prime Minister's Office]] and the Downing Street Press Office.
==History== Various political advisers have in the past acted in a press secretary role; [[Francis Williams (journalist)|Francis Williams]], a journalist who had served in the [[Ministry of Information (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Information]] during the [[Second World War]], served under [[Clement Attlee]],<ref name="Seymour-Ure 1998">{{Cite report|author=|authorlink=|coauthors=|date=April 1998|title=Memorandum submitted by Colin Seymour-Ure, Professor of Government, University of Kent at Canterbury|url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm199798/cmselect/cmpubadm/770/77021.htm|publisher=[[Public Administration Select Committee]]|page=|docket=|accessdate=29 September 2015|quote=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930150506/http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm199798/cmselect/cmpubadm/770/77021.htm|archivedate=30 September 2015|df=}}</ref> as 'Adviser on Public Relations'.<ref name="Seymour-Ure 2008">{{cite book|last1=Seymour-Ure|first1=Colin|title=Prime Ministers and the Media: Issues of Power and Control|date=2003|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|isbn=0631187677}}</ref> [[Winston Churchill]] shunned the role, and did not appoint anyone to the role until several months into his premiership, when he hired Fife Clark.<ref name="Seymour-Ure 2008" /> In 1997 Alastair Campbell was appointed by then-Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]]. When [[David Cameron]] was elected, Gabby Bertin who had previously served as the head of press for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] became the Downing Street Press Secretary.<ref name="Singleton 2013">{{cite news|last1=Singleton|first1=David|title=Warning to Cameron as Tory advisers take Downing Street comms jobs|url=http://www.prweek.com/article/1004252/warning-cameron-tory-advisers-downing-street-comms-jobs|accessdate=29 September 2015|work=[[PR Week]]|date=19 May 2013}}</ref> She was later replaced by Susie Squire in 2012.<ref name="Owens 2012">{{cite news|last1=Owens|first1=John|title=Prime Minister picks Jean-Christophe Gray and Susie Squire for top comms roles|url=http://www.prweek.com/article/1157508/prime-minister-picks-jean-christophe-gray-susie-squire-top-comms-roles|accessdate=29 September 2015|work=[[PR Week]]|date=31 October 2012}}</ref> In July 2016 when [[Theresa May]] became Prime Minister, [[Lizzie Loudon]] was appointed as her Press Secretary. Following the resignation of Loudon in April 2017, Paul Harrison took over the role after the general election on 8 June.
